{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20873"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20873"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.91,0.09,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13748"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13748","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13748"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79180"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12328"},{"type":"tags","id":"12693"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33098"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents with fatigue, weight loss, and peripheral oedema. Tissue biopsy reveals extracellular deposits that stain with Congo red and show apple-green birefringence under polarized light.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of amyloidosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deposition of fibrillar aggregates of misfolded proteins","Accumulation of starch-like polysaccharides","Excessive production of collagen by fibroblasts","Intracellular accumulation of lipid-rich material","Precipitation of calcium phosphate crystals"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of amyloidosis involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Edeposition of fibrillar aggregates of misfolded proteins\u003C/strong\u003E. Normally, proteins maintain a specific three-dimensional structure that keeps them soluble. In amyloidosis, these proteins become misfolded and aggregate into insoluble fibrils that deposit in the extracellular space of various tissues and organs, leading to tissue damage and functional compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese amyloid deposits bind various components including proteoglycans, glycosaminoglycans (such as heparan sulfate and dermatan sulfate), and plasma proteins (notably serum amyloid P component). These associated molecules contribute to the characteristic staining properties of amyloid, including Congo red positivity and apple-green birefringence under polarized light.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccumulation of starch-like polysaccharides\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect. Despite the name \u0027amyloid\u0027 (which derives from the Latin \u0027amylum\u0027 meaning starch) being given due to staining characteristics that resembled starch, amyloid deposits are primarily protein-based, not polysaccharide-based.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntracellular accumulation of lipid-rich material\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes other storage diseases like Gaucher disease or Niemann-Pick disease, not amyloidosis. Amyloid deposits are extracellular, not intracellular.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive production of collagen by fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes fibrosis or scarring, not amyloidosis. While both involve extracellular protein accumulation, the proteins and mechanisms differ.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrecipitation of calcium phosphate crystals\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes calcification or mineralization processes, not amyloidosis. Amyloid deposits are protein-based fibrils, not mineral crystals.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amyloidosis is characterized by extracellular deposits of fibrillar proteins formed from misfolded proteins that aggregate into insoluble fibrils.","Amyloid deposits bind proteoglycans, glycosaminoglycans, and plasma proteins like serum amyloid P component, which contribute to their staining properties.","The term \u0027amyloid\u0027 originated from the starch-like staining characteristics of these deposits, though they are not actually related to starch."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; page 259."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79180"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20873"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79180"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T08:29:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T08:30:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13748"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the